{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17635366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17635366"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:12:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:12:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17541"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17541"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.7,0,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10231"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74668"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10231"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17541"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60151"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7236"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23928"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23931"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74668"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding nerve supply to the lower limb is crucial for clinical assessment of movement disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is involved in both hip extension and knee flexion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Obturator nerve","Sciatic nerve","Superficial fibular nerve","Tibial nerve","Deep fibular nerve"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esciatic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the posterior thigh muscles (hamstrings) which perform both hip extension and knee flexion. As the largest peripheral nerve in the body, it divides into the tibial and common fibular nerves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options have different functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eobturator nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies:    \u003Cul\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EMedial thigh muscles\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EHip adduction movements\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperficial fibular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies:    \u003Cul\u003E    \u003Cli\u003ELateral compartment of leg\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EFoot eversion\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etibial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies:    \u003Cul\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EPosterior leg muscles\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EFoot plantarflexion\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EToe flexion\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edeep fibular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies:    \u003Cul\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EAnterior leg muscles\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EFoot dorsiflexion\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EToe extension\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The sciatic nerve innervates the hamstring muscles which perform hip extension and knee flexion","The sciatic nerve divides into tibial and common fibular nerves in the posterior thigh","Major peripheral nerves typically supply specific muscle compartments with distinct functions"],"references":["Giuffre BA, Black AC, Jeanmonod R. Anatomy, Sciatic Nerve. 2023 Nov 16. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29494038.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatom